</li></ul></li></ul></li><li id="tree_64338237" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64338237" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64338237" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64338237" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64338237" name="comment_link_64338237" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266707&amp;cid=64338237" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64338237)" >Accelerator not Reactor</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64338237" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64338237); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore">Roger W Moore</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore">( 538166 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64338237">		
		on Saturday March 23, 2024 @03:21AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266707&amp;cid=64338237">#64338237</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore/journal/" title="Monday April 13, 2009 @07:10PM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64338237">What they are doing is not a fusion reactor it's simply a small proton particle accelerator with boron injected into the beam. While they do not seem to state the thrust this thing generates it's essentially an incremental improvement on an ion-thruster so I expect it will be tiny. Particle accelerators have been able to produce fusion reactions for years - indeed even the first-ever accelerators produced by Cockcroft and Walton in the 1920s could do that using nothing more than a van der Graff.
<br> <br>
Accelerators are useless for power generation because only a tiny number of nuclei are involved and it takes way more energy to make it happen than it produces. This also means that the thrust will be tiny because only a handful of nuclei will react. So technically (if it does work) it is a fusion-based thruster but it is way less exciting that they are trying to make it sound.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64338237">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64338237" class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266707&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64338237" onclick="D2.replyTo(64338237); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266707&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64338165" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64338165)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
