</li></ul></li><li id="tree_64338751" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64338751" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64338751" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64338751" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64338751" name="comment_link_64338751" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266707&amp;cid=64338751" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64338751)" >Related, but different</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64338751" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64338751); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~dpilot">dpilot</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~dpilot">( 134227 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64338751"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64338751"><p>As for using boron and expecting nuclear things to happen, there is something similar that is already a thing.  It's called boron-neutron capture therapy.  It involves a chemotherapy medication that is not yet active.  It incorporates boron in its structure, but is not actually active until the boron captures a neutron and transmutes into carbon.  The idea is to inject the medication then aim a neutron beam at the tumor.  The substance is transmuted at the beam and becomes active - but only there.</p><p><span class="substr"> </span> <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7952987/" title="nih.gov">https://ww</a> [nih.gov]</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64338751">

